{{Infobox_nrhp | name =Thayer Public Library | nrhp_type = | image=Thayer Public Library, Braintree MA.jpg | caption=Current library, built 1999 | location= [[Braintree, Massachusetts]] | lat_degrees = 42 | lat_minutes = 12 | lat_seconds = 24.2 | lat_direction = N | long_degrees = 71 | long_minutes = 0 | long_seconds = 17.8 | long_direction = W | locmapin = Massachusetts | area = | built =1874 | architect = [[Hammatt Billings]] & Joseph E. Billings | architecture= [[Renaissance architecture|Renaissance]] | added = July 21, 1978 | governing_body = Local | refnum=78000446<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|no date specified}}</ref> }} [[File:Braintree Old Library.jpg|thumb|Original library (1874-1953) Listed on the U.S. National Register of Historic Places]] The '''Thayer Public Library''' is a public [[library]] located in the town of [[Braintree, Massachusetts]] with 102,000 [[book]]s, 200 [[Magazine|periodical]] subscriptions, and 8,000 [[videotape|videos]], [[DVD]]s, music [[Compact Disk|CDs]], and [[audiobook]]s.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.thayerpubliclibrary.net/about.html Thayer Public Library, About the Library<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The library is a member of the [[Old Colony Library Network]].<ref>[http://www.ocln.org/wp-public/?page_id=24 Old Colony Library Network<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
==About the library== The library is named for [[Sylvanus Thayer|General Sylvanus Thayer]],<ref name=autogenerated1 /> who helped found it through a $20,000 bequest in his will. The original building was dedicated June 4, 1874, and opened to the public in September of the same year.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> It operated as a library until 1953, when it was replaced by a larger building across the street.<ref>[http://www.thayerpubliclibrary.net/about.html About]</ref> The 1874 building was occupied by the Braintree Water Department for many years, but is currently vacant. This building is included in the [[List of Registered Historic Places in Norfolk County, Massachusetts]].<ref>[http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/MA/Norfolk/state.html National Register of Historical Places - MASSACHUSETTS (MA), Norfolk County<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
In 1997 the 1953 library building was razed to and replaced by the current three-story brick [[Postmodern architecture|postmodern]] building that opened in 1999.
==Antitrust lawsuit participation== In March 2008, the Thayer Public Library was notified that it was among several libraries in [[Massachusetts]] that would share in the 2002 settlement of an [[antitrust]] case that was brought against [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]], [[EMI Music]], [[Warner-Elektra-Atlantic|Warner Music Group]], and [[Sony Music Entertainment]]<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/5226945/ Librarians: Free CDs too much of a good thing - U.S. news - MSNBC.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> by the [[antitrust]] division of [[Attorney General of Massachusetts|Massachusetts Attorney General]] [[Martha Coakley]]âs office, along with the Attorneys General of thirty-nine other states. The lawsuit was settled in 2002 for $144 million, and alleged that the music distribution companies illegally inflated the price of CDs by requiring retailers to sell them at or above a set level in order to qualify for substantial advertising funding.<ref>''[[The New York Times]]'', October 1, 2002</ref>
The library is expected to receive a minimum of $300, which must be used exclusively for its music related programs or projects.<ref>''[[The Patriot Ledger]]'', March 8, 2008</ref>
